# Raspberry Pi Asterisk and FreePBX Setup

# Background

This guide follows install instructions from [https://github.com/playfultechnology/RasPBX](https://github.com/playfultechnology/RasPBX) which is derived from this forum post: [https://www.dslreports.com/forum/r30661088-PBX-FreePBX-for-the-Raspberry-Pi](https://www.dslreports.com/forum/r30661088-PBX-FreePBX-for-the-Raspberry-Pi)

Note: DSLReports is now closed; however, you can still access the forum post through the wayback machine: [https://web.archive.org/web/20250222040035/https://www.dslreports.com/forum/r30661088-PBX-FreePBX-for-the-Raspberry-Pi](https://web.archive.org/web/20250222040035/https://www.dslreports.com/forum/r30661088-PBX-FreePBX-for-the-Raspberry-Pi)

There are modifications as they are using windows and this guide is for Macs and Linux.

# Hardware

Raspberry Pi 4b or newer  
32GB Micro SD Card or higher  
FlyingVoice FTA1101 VoIP Adapter

# Step 1

Setup RaspberryPi OS

1. Download the installer tool from the raspberry pi website: [https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/](https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/)
2. Run through the install guide by choosing a Pi device, the newest Raspberry Pi OS and the micro sd card storage device to burn the OS to.
   1. Note: This guide was tested with the full Raspberry Pi OS that includes a GUI; however, we do not use the GUI at all. You will likely be able to follow the same instructions with the RaspberryPi OS Lite version.
3. Ddd default configurations
   1. Create a default account with a password
      1. Username: pi
      2. Password: Whatever you want
   2. Enable SSH
   3. Connect to Wifi (If you plan on using wifi instead of ethernet)
      1. Enter your Wifi Name and password
4.
5. Once Complete, plug the micro sd card into the Pi and turn the pi on.

# Step 2 - SSH into the Raspberry Pi

First, you will need to determine what the IP Address of your raspberry pi is. You can do this in a variety of ways.

## Option 1 - Look at your Wifi Router Device Table

The instructions for this vary based on the type of router you have; however, all routers have a list of devices currently connected to them.

1. Log into your router's admin panel
2. Find the table of devices currently connected
3. Find a device named RaspberryPi
   1. Take note of it’s IP address and MAC Address
4. Done

## Option 2 - Get it from the Pi itself

Note: this option will require you to connect the Pi to a monitor via HDMI (Note, Pis use either a micro HDMI or mini HDMI cables) and to a keyboard

1. Connect the Pi to a monitor
2. Open the terminal (if you are using the lite version, you should only be in a terminal)
3. Run command `ifconfig`
4. Under the wlan section, take note of the IP address listed. It should be something like 192.168.1.X
   1. Note: it is not going to be 192.168.1.0 or 192.168.1.1, that is likely your routers IP Address

To be clear, if you are performing Option 2, you do not need to use SSH to communicate with the Pi, it just makes it easier for copy pasting commands.

Next, SSH into the Pi from your development computer.

Run

```sh
ssh <pi_username>@<pi_ip_address>
```

It will ask you something about fingerprinting, just type “yes”

Enter your password that you setup in the OS configuration page

# Step 3 - Copy the Install Scripts from The RasPBX Repo

Full instructions coming soon but just download the repo onto the Raspberry Pi:  
[https://github.com/playfultechnology/RasPBX](https://github.com/playfultechnology/RasPBX)

Run `cd RasPBX` to get into the directory

# Step 4 - Executing the install script

Run the following commands to make the install script executable and then execute it

```shell
chmod +x install
sudo ./install
```

- When prompted enter the following settings
  - Set pi user password
    - This can be the same as the one you already use
  - Set root user password
    - Anything you want
  - Select FreePBX version
    - Recommended: 17
  - Select Asterisk version
    - Recommended: 22
  - Use Edge?
    - Yes (**Note**: IDK what this does)
  - Disable IPv6 option?
    - Yes

It will ask you to review and accept your configurations

# Step 5 - RaspberryOS Configuration

A configure page will pop up. Change the following settings

1. System Options->Set Hostname (1/S4) RasPBX
2. Localisation Options->Locale (5/L1) en_GB.UTF-8
3. Localisation Options->Timezone (5/L2) Europe - London
4. Advanced Options->Expand Filesystem (6/A1)
5. Finish/Reboot Now **No**

Note: Do not reboot when asked. The script will take care of that for you.

Once you have finished, the Pi will reboot and it will end you SSH session.

Once the Pi is rebooted you are going to SSH in again under the **new root user.** If you made the password different for root, enter that one in when prompted.

```shell
ssh root@<pi_ip_address>
```

For all future reboots, you will be logging in as root.  
When you login as root, the script will continue where it left off.

Note: During the installation process, it is possible the fingerprint ssh may change. If it does you will get the following error:

If this happens simply run:

```shell
ssh-keygen -R <pi_ip_address>
```

This will clear the stored fingerprint and allow you to SSH in again.

## Step 6 - Continuing the installation (30-45 minutes)

Once you log back in as root, your installation will automatically continue.

It will ask you to re-confirm your settings and then continue.

You may encounter a warning  
![][image1]

If you do, just click enter which will default to N  
Note: IDK if that is the right choice or not but it worked for me.

The Pi will reboot a few more times, keep logging back in as root. If you need to reset the fingerprint on mac, do so with the command above.

At the very end, it will say  
“FreePBX Installation Complete”

# Step 7 - Setup FTA1101

This setup guide is to connect the FTA1101 to the local raspberry pi only network. This ensures the device does not have internet connection and is only available via the Raspberry Pi interface. For our use case, we don’t need direct network access

Connect the ethernet cable from the FTA1101 device’s LAN port to your development computer's ethernet port. Note: Make sure it is the LAN port specifically.

On your computer navigate to 192.168.1.1

1. Username: admin
2. Password: admin

## Step 1 - Setup SIP Account

Navigate to **SIP Account > Line 1**

1. Enable Line1.
2. Under Proxy Server enter your Pi’s IP:
   1. Proxy Server: 192.168.11.1
   2. Proxy Port: 5060
3. Fill out the following fields
4. Phone Number
   1. An extension number (ex. 1000)
5. Account
   1. The same number you put as the phone number
6. Password
   1. Extension secret (this can be anything but remember what it is for later)
7. DTMF Type (This is important for capturing the numbers inputted into the phone)
   1. RFC2933

Click Save and Apply

## Step 2 - Set the correct Dial Tone

Navigate to **Phone > Preferences**

1. Tone Type
   1. Select the Country you want your tone to be

## Step 3 - Prepare device for local WAN

Navigate to **Network > WAN**

Enter the following settings:

1. WAN IP Mode
   1. Static
2. IP Address
   1. 192.168.11.2
3. Subnet Mask
   1. 255.255.255.0
4. Primary DNS
   1. 8.8.8.8

Click Save & Apply.

The device will automatically reboot. This will likely disconnect you from the device. It should come back up in a minute or so.

Once back up, login again and verify the settings we saved in **Network > WAN**

## Step 4 - Setup Pi Connection

Unplug the ethernet cable from the FTA1101 and your computer.

Plug in the ethernet cable to the WAN port on the FTA1101 and the ethernet port on your Raspberry Pi

`FTA1101 WAN -> Raspberry Pi Ethernet`

SSH into the Pi and run the following command

```shell
sudo nmtui
```

- Select “Edit a connection”, choose your eth0 or Wired connection 1, then Edit.
- Under IPv4 Configuration, set:
  - Method: Manual
  - Addresses: e.g. 192.168.11.1/24
- Gateway: leave blank for a point-to-point link
- Save and Activate the connection.

Verify that the Pi can see the device

```bash
nmcli device status        # shows DEVICE, TYPE, STATE
nmcli connection show      # verify your manual settings
ip addr show eth0
```

You should see something like:

`eth0           ethernet  connected     Wired connection 1`

Then attempt to ping the new IP with the following command

```bash
ping 192.168.11.2
```

If you see a message like: `From 192.168.11.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable`, please ensure you have followed the instructions correctly and try again.

# Step 8 - Setting up FreePBX

FreePBX is a web GUI. To access this web gui remotely, you need to create an SSH tunnel which will bind the PIs FreePBX port with your development computer.

To do this run the following command  
Note: This command binds both the FreePBX port as well as the FTA1101 adapter port. If you aren’t using a FTA1101 device, omit `-L 192.168.11.2:80`.

**Open a new terminal window on your development computer and enter the following command**

```shell
ssh -L 8000:localhost:80 -L 8080:192.168.11.2:80 root@192.168.0.209
```

Enter your SSH password for the root user.

Then in your Mac browser:

- http://localhost:8000 → FreePBX/Asterisk GUI on the Pi
- http://localhost:8080 → FTA1101’s interface

To close this connection at any time, use CTRL + D to logout

## FreePBX Admin Setup

Go to [http://localhost:8000](http://localhost:8000) in your local web browser.

The first time you come here you will need to setup an account  
![][image2]

1. Username
   1. admin
2. Password
   1. Any password you want

I left the other configurations default for now.

## Setup SIP Settings

1. In the Admin Panel click FreePBX Administration
2. Enter your admin credentials
3. If prompted about language, select the language you prefer.
4. Navigate to **Settings > Asterisk SIP Settings**
5. Click Detect Network Settings
   1. This should auto populate the following settings
      1. Blank / Blank
      2. 192.168.0.0 / 24
      3. 192.168.11.0 / 24
6. Click Submit in the bottom right corner

## Setting up a new SIP Phone Extension

1. In the Admin Panel click FreePBX Administration
2. Enter your admin credentials
3. Navigate to **Connectivity > Extensions**
4. Click **Add Extension** and select **Add New SIP [chan_pjsip] Extension**
5. Fill out the following information:
   1. User Extension
      1. 1000
   2. Display Name
      1. Whatever you want
   3. Secret
      1. The password you entered when setting up the Phone
6. Click Submit in the bottom right corner
7. Click Apply Config red button in the top right corner

**After this has been configured, Reboot the FTA1101 Device.**

## Verify Asterisk Can See the Phone Line

You should now see the FTA1101 register in both its own UI and in FreePBX’s **Reports > Asterisk Info > Registries**. Once “Registered” shows, your ATA can place and receive calls via your locally-hosted Asterisk.

## Enable ARI API for External Application Integration

In FreePBX GUI, go **Settings > Asterisk Rest Interface Users**.

1. Create a new user
2. Enter a username and password
3. Click Save and Apply Config

### Verify & enable the built-in HTTP server

FreePBX uses Asterisk’s internal HTTP server on port 8088 by default. ARI cannot function if that server is disabled.

1. Log in to the FreePBX GUI as an administrator.
2. Navigate to Settings → Advanced Settings.
3. Scroll to Asterisk Built-in mini-HTTP server:
   1. Set Enable the mini-HTTP Server to Yes
   2. Leave HTTP Prefix blank (removing any “0” or other value) to avoid ARI errors
   3. Confirm Bind Address is either 0.0.0.0 (all interfaces) or the Pi’s ethernet IP (e.g. 192.168.11.2)
4. Click Submit in the bottom right corner of the screen

### Enable the ARI server itself

ARI must be explicitly turned on in Advanced Settings.

1. Stay in Settings → Advanced Settings (with readonly fields visible).
2. Find Asterisk REST Interface
   1. Set Enable the Asterisk REST Interface to Yes
3. Click Submit
4. Click Apply Config red button in the top right corner

Verify with:

```bash
curl -u <api-username>:<password> [http://127.0.0.1:8088/ari/applications](http://127.0.0.1:8088/ari/applications)
```

You should see your phone-app listed.

## Setup Catch-All Dialplan

This will catch all of the phone numbers dialed from a particular extension and route them to your application instead. This configuration will ring until your server answers the phone. **It disabled the max timeout**.

1. Create a custom dialplan

   1. Open the FreePBX Admin Panel
   2. Navigate to **Admin** > **Config Edit**
   3. Find **extension_custom.conf** and click it
   4. Add the following code:

   ```text
   [ari-outbound]
   exten => _X.,1,NoOp(Outbound call to ARI)
   same => n,Progress()
   same => n,Playtones(ring)
   same => n,Stasis(phone-app)

   [ari-outbound]
   exten => _X.,1,NoOp(Internal call to ${EXTEN}, SKIP_STASIS=${SKIP_STASIS})
   same => n,GotoIf($["${SKIP_STASIS}" = "true"]?ring)
   same => n,Stasis(phone-app)    ; only trunks or plain inbound hit here
   same => n(ring),Dial(PJSIP/${EXTEN},20)
   same => n,Hangup()
   ```

2. Click **Save** and **Apply Config**
3. Update your extension to use the new dialplan
   1. Go to Connectivity > Extensions
   2. Click the Edit button next to the extension you want to route
   3. Click the Advanced tab
   4. Find **Context** and change the value to:
      1. ari-outbound
   5. **Submit** and **Apply Changes**

# Developing Locally

To hit the API locally, we can use the same ssh tunnel technique we use for the admin panels.

1. FreePBX Admin Panel: [http://localhost:8000/](http://localhost:8000/)
2. FlyingVoice FTA1101 Admin Panel: http://localhost:8080/

```bash
ssh -L 8000:localhost:80 -L 8080:192.168.11.2:80 -L 8088:localhost:8088 root@192.168.0.209
```

We added 8088:localhost:8088 which is the default port for the Asterisk API
